Here's a simple explanation and implementation:

The `debounce` function delays the execution of a function until after a specified wait time has elapsed since the last time it was called, preventing rapid repeated calls.

```javascript
function debounce(func, wait) {
  let timeout;
  return function(...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeout);
    timeout = setTimeout(() => func.apply(this, args), wait);
  };
}

// Example usage:
const handleResize = debounce(() => {
  console.log('Window resized!');
}, 300);

window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);
```

In this example, the `handleResize` function will only execute 300ms after the last resize event, rather than on every event.
